    {
      "id": "0ceb358a23271889db18cc5aec2abcdc17ea3fc0",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 377,
        "name": "wc-checkpatch",
        "username": "hpdd-checkpatch",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2014-04-30 23:25:36.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nLooks good to me.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "b254f7ebd388da172a299ec1d3be3c12265ab34b",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2014-05-01 02:13:30.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI don't quite understand this. A volatile file should not leave a filename in the filesystem if it is working properly. If that is not happening there is a bug somewhere in the code, or the client is running in interop testing mode?\n\nThat said, if this is not a Lustre filesystem then it is ok to do this - it will leave an open-unlinked file as intended, so this patch is itself ok.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "20f2f4a61fccc7ec4e568f658987805dc2c29fa0",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2014-05-01 02:15:39.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1\n\nWhile the patch is itself ok for cases where the client is running against an old server, I don't think this will fix the problem with the orphan inodes in the filesystem.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "a8f0b90bababc7998c9a6381c429ae48f93257ac",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 292,
        "name": "James Nunez",
        "email": "jnunez@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jnunez"
      },
      "date": "2014-05-01 03:51:08.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nThanks for the comments. No, volatile files are not being left in the file system. The problem we are trying to address is unattached inodes being left by volatile files and the thought is that we need to reduce the nlink count of volatile files. Should we just look for volatile files in close or after they are used in lfs migrate and multiop and decrement the nlink count then?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "c926e93d0d06d4aad62f7bae0aee450ef4f4bbdc",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 2,
        "name": "Jenkins",
        "username": "hudson",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2014-05-01 08:41:26.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nBuild Started http://build.whamcloud.com/job/lustre-reviews/23563/",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "b72c0189e9ec534a3283ebc73882ad14be2189bb",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 2,
        "name": "Jenkins",
        "username": "hudson",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2014-05-01 08:58:42.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Verified+1\n\nBuild Successful \n \nhttp://build.whamcloud.com/job/lustre-reviews/23563/ : SUCCESS",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "e97390eb9fe845092c2e76c59f3f7f977905bf1e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2014-05-01 10:22:30.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nIn case it wasn't clear, the patch calling \"unlink(file_path)\" would fail on a Lustre filesystem with volatile files because there _is_ no pathname to unlink as soon as the open() completes. Maybe \"volatile\" is a bad name, implying \"easily destroyed\", when in fact they should be called \"nameless\" or \"temporary\" as they are in newer upstream kernels (O_TMPFILE).\n\nThe only reason I gave the patch +1 is because it fixes the problem of new clients on an old MDS (or on a non-Lustre filesystem) where \"volatile\" files do not exist, and all that this function would do is create a real file with a strange name that would not be deleted at close time as expected. Adding the unlink() at the end fixes this problem.\n\nTo really fix this bug needs a fix on the MDS. In mds_open_reint() (or similar, can't check the code right now) it should drop the nlink as soon as open as soon as the file open is completed and before the file handle is returned to the client. It should also put the file into the PENDING directory like any other open-unlinked file. That way, when the file is closed or the client crashes it will be automatically deleted.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "8635f6bfd8875ebcc945bb3d0e8ac862aa640599",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 292,
        "name": "James Nunez",
        "email": "jnunez@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jnunez"
      },
      "date": "2014-05-02 03:52:38.000000000",
      "message": "Uploaded patch set 2.",
